Lesson Series 2: Wellness & Self-Care

*The Future We Are We*, 2020\. Ink on Paper. 27 x 55 inches.

**Workshop: Drawing Our Way to Calm**

Lesson goals: 

* Practice a simple breathing technique    
* Discuss how mindfulness can help calm feelings of stress and anxiety  
* Thoughtfully observe a piece of art

Resources: 

* Feelings Wheel: [https://feelingswheel.com](https://feelingswheel.com/)  
* Feelings Chart example: [https://www.partnershipforchildren.org.uk/uploads/Files/PDFs/Resilience%20Activities/Feelings%20Activities.pdf](https://www.partnershipforchildren.org.uk/uploads/Files/PDFs/Resilience%20Activities/Feelings%20Activities.pdf) 

5 mins		Introduction (to be read aloud by teacher or student volunteers): 

| Meet Shantell\! She is a curious and adventurous girl from London who draws all day long \- on her clothes, bags, journals, friends, shoes, and even the street outside of her apartment. When she starts moving her pen she tries not to stop, and the lines curve, flow, and wander from her body through her hand, often feeling like they mirror the way she feels inside.  |
| :---- |

Shantell woke up one morning with a strange fluttering in her chest. As she got up and ready for school, she noticed that the fluttering feeling stayed there, as though butterflies had moved into her body and were having a little party. She shook out her hands and feet, but the feeling remained. 

As she got closer to school, the feeling started to move into her arms, and down her legs. “What could this be?” Shantell asked herself. Her mind started racing as she considered that this was part of having big feelings, which can be difficult, fun, and exciting, but she needed a way to understand and move through what was happening. 

Shantell remembered something she’d learned in class the previous week about ways to deal with anxiety and feelings of stress: deep breathing. Slowly and carefully, Shantell breathed in and out, in and out, until the butterfly sensation slowly started to disappear. 

Today, we are going to explore ways of managing big emotions with deep breathing.

5 mins		Warm-up

* Take a look at the feelings chart. Pick a face that best describes how you are feeling today. 

![][image1]![][image2]![][image3]

* Group conversation: Describe your mood using a color. It doesn't have to be your favorite color, just one that feels like it describes how you are feeling right in this moment.

* *If there’s more time:*  
  Quick write\! Get a pen and paper. In a few minutes, write about what is taking up space in your mind today. 

10 mins	Two-part breathing

* Sit in a circle.   
* Practice 2-part breathing:   
  * Place one hand on your stomach, and the other on your chest.   
  * Breathe into the belly and feel your stomach expand, then continue breathing into your chest and feel it rise.  
  * Exhale.   
* Do five rounds of 2-part breathing. Modify by counting to five during each inhale and exhale.  
    
* For the Teacher: You can snap your fingers at each part of the two-part breathing exercise to the rhythm of a calm heartbeat, such as:  
  * (1) Belly  
  * (2) Chest  
  * (3) Exhale  
  * (4) Exhale  
  * (5) Exhale   
  * Then repeat\! 

10 mins		Art Observation

* Look at the piece of art by Shantell Martin, *The Future We Are We* (above), and follow the lines with your eyes.   
* Talk about the art:  
  * What do you feel when you look at this picture? (Show feelings chart)  
  * What do you notice about the faces in the image? How are they feeling?   
  * Do you see a line or part of the drawing that feels like ‘you’ at this moment? Which one, and why?  
  * Try to read the letters and words in the image. What is this piece about? 

10 mins	Drawing Exercise

* While focusing on your breath, draw a single line that represents how you are feeling right now. Use Shantell’s art as a guide. Your drawing does not need to look like Shantell’s, or like anyone else’s; it is just for you to explore how breathing makes you feel.

* Next, create your own 2-part breathing drawing\!   
  * Breathe into your chest, then belly, and exhale.  
  * Draw one line.  
  * Breathe into your chest, then belly, and exhale.   
  * Draw your next line.   
  * You can add faces, people, buildings, trees, words, whatever you’d like. . 

5 min	Wrap-up/Group Discussion

Do a body scan \- close your eyes and focus on every part of your body from your head to your toes.

* What do you usually do when you feel like there are a lot of things going on inside of you?   
* What was new or different about the breathing exercise?   
* Does breathing change how you feel in your body?  
* What else can help you feel calm?

Share your artwork.

* What do the lines in your drawing represent?  
* What surprised you about this process?  
* How or when can you bring breathing exercises into your everyday life?   
* What changed in your body or your drawings after doing the 2-part breathing? 

---

* Additional activities:   
  * Body Scan: close your eyes and examine every tiny part of your body (top of the head, eyebrows, eyes, cheeks, mouth, jaw, etc.) without talking  
  * Line Storytelling: Think of something that happened on the way to school today, and draw it by using one continuous line.  
  * Mind Maps: Draw the pathway you take to school, and add details of what you see on your journey: streets, shops, buildings, people \- your entire commute\!
